<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,461,796]" pageId="12" pageNumber="45">
Trees and shrubs 
<quantity box="[413,490,577,603]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="45" unit="m" value="5.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="3.0">3–7 m</quantity>
tall. Morphologicaly similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Candolle" authorityYear="1828" baseAuthorityName="G. Mey." box="[881,1079,577,602]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrcia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="12" pageNumber="45" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="sylvatica">
<emphasis box="[881,1079,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="45">Myrcia sylvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs by having elliptic leaves and a flat or raised midvein on the adaxial lamina surface; it differs from other 
<taxonomicName box="[1214,1396,616,642]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrcia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="12" pageNumber="45" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1214,1300,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="45">Myrcia</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by having a pilose hypanthium and style and by having ellipsoid fruit.
</paragraph>
